ative and socially conscious ways. Outlining how toys shaped and were shaped by radical visions, Goldberg locates the moment Americans first came to understand the world of toys—from Barbie to G.I. Joe—as much more than child’s play.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack dollsxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aChildrenxSocial life and customsy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aParentingxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPlayxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aToysxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aToysxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aWar toysxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027102?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027102/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles